definition.val: A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.
Temporal interval that defines opossum life from the prenatal stage until late adult stage.
Opossum life cycle that starts with fertilization and ends with birth.

comments: Gestation time is 15 days of development (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Monodelphis_domestica).

definition.val: Opossum developmental stage that covers the period from birth until 4 months old, when individuals reach sexual maturity.

comments: Male and female opossum reach sexual maturity by 122 days of age (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Monodelphis_domestica).

definition.val: Nursing stage that refers to the first 2 weeks period when the young is permanently attached to the nipple.

comments: Immediately after birth, the neonate is attached to the nipple for 2 weeks before being transferred to the nest or carried on the mother's back (see http://www.faunaparaguay.com/mamm10Monodelphisdomestica.pdf). Note that unlike many other marsupials, females do not have a pouch [WP]. [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gray_short-tailed_opossum]

definition.val: Immature stage that covers the period from 2 months old (age of weaning) until 4 months old, before sexual maturity.
Opossum developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult opossum, which is usually over 4 months old.
Mature stage that refers to a adult opossum which is over 4 months and under 21 months old.

comments: The life span of opossums is very short. The average female probably lives through one breeding season (see http://www.mspca.org/programs/wildlife-resources/species-information/about-opossums.html). In the wild, two years is the standard lifespan (http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Monodelphis_domestica/). We decided to consider 21 months as the upper limit for breeding age, before aged stage.

comments: The life span of opossums is very short. The average female probably lives through one breeding season (see http://www.mspca.org/programs/wildlife-resources/species-information/about-opossums.html). In the wild, two years is the standard lifespan (http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Monodelphis_domestica/). We arbitraly consider 20 months as the upper limit for the adult, before aged stage. This is to improve as far as information is available.

definition.val: Aged stage that refers to a opossum which is over 21 and under 22 months old.

Immature stage that covers the period from birth until weaning, at about 2 months old. This stage includes the first 2 weeks period when the young is permanently attached to the nipple.
Nursing stage that covers the period from 2 weeks old, when the young is transferred to the nest or carried on the mother's back, until about 2 months old (age of weaning).
Infant stage that refers to an infant opossum which is over 2 and under 3 weeks old.
Infant stage that refers to an infant opossum which is over 3 and under 4 weeks old.

Infant stage that refers to an infant opossum which is over 6 and under 7.5 weeks old, the time when usually opossum weaning occurs.
Infant stage that refers to a 2-week-old opossum which is over 14 and under 15 days old.

Count of number of days intervening between the end of the stage and the time of birth according to a reference model. Note that the first day of post-birth development has the value of 1 for this property, and the period during which the child is one day old has the value 2

comments: This is a shortcut annotation that can be expanded to an OWL axiom, or to a set of OWL axioms. The exact translation has yet to be determined, and may be application-dependent.

Subset consisting of classes describing highly granular developmental stages (for instance, '23-year-old'). Such stages might be useful for annotation purpose, but might be folded into less granular parents for display purpose.
Used to associate a measurement property (e.g. days post fertilization) with a unit (e.g. days)
